  "text": "is the number of the instances which support these other combinations . The confidence of a rule is a measure of a rule's validity representing the strength of a unique rule pattern against contradictory rule patterns which refer to the other rule patterns which have the same antecedent combination but with different consequent. Scaled rule confidence is calculated by taking the ratio between the number of instances representing a unique rule pattern and the number of the instances representing the contradictory rules' patterns . Equation (7) shows the calculation of scaled rule confidence as described in [CITATION_1] . (7) Step3, Calculation of Scaled Rule Weights, in this step, the unique rules' patterns resulting from the previous step were weighted by calculating a scaled fuzzy weight for each of the patterns. The scaled fuzzy weight is calculated as a product of the scaled fuzzy support and the scaled confidence as shown in (8) and described in [CITATION_2] .",
